ield of Stable Isotope Geochemistry. In terms of new technology, new sub-disciplines, and numbers of researchers, the field has changed more in the past decade than in any other since that of its birth. Unlike the 1986 volume, which was restricted to high temperature fields, this book covers a wider range of disciplines. However, it would not be possible to fit a comprehensive review into a single volume. Our goal is to provide state-of-the-art reviews in chosen subjects that have emerged or advanced greatly since 1986. This volume was prepared for Short Course on Stable Isotope Geochemistry presented November 2-4, 2001 in conjunction with the annual meetings of the Geological Society of America in Boston, Massachusetts.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 4aGeochemie. 4aGesteinskunde. 4aIsotopengeochemie. 4aMetamorphose. 4aStabiles Isotop. 7aSCIENCE / Earth Sciences / Mineralogy.2bisacsh1 aAlley, Richard B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBaumgartner, Lukas P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCanfield, D. E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChacko, Thomas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChakraborty, Sumit, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCole, David R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCole, David R., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCuffey, Kurt M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDes Marais, David J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEiler, John M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFreeman, Katherine H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/c